snippet.textDisplay:
It must be noted that SOME viruses have a lipid coating surrounding the protein shell of their capsid. NOT ALL do. But of course, the protection of the lipid jacket is what makes some viruses like coronavirus highly survivable outside of a host organism. This fatty outer layer is similar to how most insects protect themselves. And simple soap strips the waxy shield off them too, causing our six-legged pestilent friends to dehydrate to death. Bacteria on the other hand (pun not intended) ARE NOT composed of a similarly simple outer lipid coating. Soap and water only serve a mechanical purpose on them; they essentially wash bacteria away unharmed with the grime, oils and dirt off our bodies. The fatty acids of salt that make up soap do not chemically attach to the bacteria exterior, rupturing or otherwise killing them. But high concentrations of topical alcohol will indeed do an effective job of that.

So remember, coronavirus is not the only microbe out there to be cautious of. Not all viruses are the same or are destroyed in the same way. Bacteria and viruses are much different. And the fact of evolution means we are only a few mutations away from a highly transmissible, far more deadly pathogen. This test run should be giving no one confidence in the world's preparedness for that eventuality.

If anything, this pandemic has proven how obliviously filthy the human animal conducts its affair on Earth.

snippet.textDisplay:
From my daughters fiancé-who works as a nurse
My unit is now a Covid19 unit. I am caring for patients bedside being ruled out for the infection and they aren’t giving us a N95 mask or respirator until they are confirmed. Idk what to do about it. Feels like COVID roulette...
It’s 2 AM. He has a fever now and left the hospital to go into quarantine but my daughter is there! He’s sooooo upset, in his car till he can get tested. He kept apologizing to me cause he feels he’s infected her too, she an accountant who’s been working from home for 2 weeks!
Please People! STAY HOME!!!!!

From Midwest Indiana
